1660744247123890179	1766628667011753938	cwolferesearch	2023-05-22 20:27:38	Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) is a valuable fine-tuning technique, but people often misunderstand how it works and the impact that it has on LLM behavior. Meta's LIMA publication provides a lot of information that puts the value of RLHF into perspective...\n\nWhat is RLHF? It’s a fine-tuning technique that can be used to improve LLM alignment. To perform RLHF, we do the following:\n- Ask a bunch of human annotators to examine instances of LLM outputs (multiple outputs for each prompt) and rank these outputs based on their preferences.\n- The manner in which we define these preferences matters a lot! For example, we could ask humans to rank incorrect information poorly, encourage interestingness, etc.\n- Train a reward model that can predict the human preference associated with each output.\n- Using the reward model, we use a reinforcement learning algorithm called Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) — see https://t.co/4nLUutpaKv — to fine-tune an LLMs parameters such that human preference is maximized.\n\nRLHF vs. SFT: The RLHF framework is super generic and can be used to optimize an LLM based on a variety of different objectives using a unified approach. The main alternative approach is supervised fine-tuning (SFT), which fine-tunes the LLM in a supervised manner using examples of dialogue data that the model should replicate. This approach was adopted by the LaMDA LLM that was/is used to power Bard, as well as the recently published LIMA paper by Meta. \n\nRLHF and SFT in InstructGPT: Notably, RLHF and SFT can be used in tandem, as demonstrated by OpenAI's InstructGPT paper. RLHF was first outlined as a method with the proposal of InstructGPT, which was eventually extended to create more powerful models like ChatGPT and GPT-4. In the InstructGPT paper, we see that RLHF can be used to create a number of desirable properties in the resulting LLM! Humans prefer the LLM more, it hallucinates less, it’s way better at following instructions, etc. Put simply, RLHF can be used to transform generic, pre-trained LLMs into the impressive information-seeking dialogue agents that we commonly see today (e.g., ChatGPT).\n\nWhat exactly is RLHF doing? This question is often misunderstood, and until now the answer has not been 100% clear. However, with recent research developments surrounding open-source LLMs and GPT-4, we know pretty clearly that the role of RLHF is to make the LLM more steerable and interesting. Notably, the model does NOT learn new information during RLHF — most knowledge and information is learned during pre-training! This fact was mentioned quite explicitly in the GPT-4 blog post (https://t.co/DtLzcc8rx6), where authors claim that RLHF can actually make the model worse at taking certain standardized exams. Plus, the recent publication of LIMA (https://t.co/gUKt1vO1Uw), which fine-tunes a model on only 1,000 curated dialogue examples and has been quite popular this week, demonstrates pretty clearly that most information comes from pre-training. Just consider the following quote:\n \n“These results strongly suggest that almost all knowledge in large language models is learned during pretraining, and only limited instruction tuning data is necessary to teach models to produce high quality output.” - from LIMA paper\n\nTL;DR: RLHF is a really powerful tool, but its sole purpose is to make the LLM more steerable (i.e., better at following instructions in a variety of different ways). RLHF does not teach the LLM new information! It just teaches the LLM how to frame/format the information that it already possesses. But, we should be aware that RLHF is not the only way to do this. From the results in LIMA, it seems like we can get similar results by just curating a small number of high-quality dialogue examples for SFT. This finding could drastically change how simple it is to create a model that is GPT-4 quality from scratch. As such, there are huge implications for open-source LLMs and overall access to this technology.	t	f	explainer	f	f
