1665830627176841217	1767931033497929016	cwolferesearch	2023-06-05 21:19:05	Foundation models are a popular topic in AI research. However, task-specific fine-tuning outperforms zero/few-shot learning with foundation models in most cases. Specialized models are hard to beat!  Luckily, recent research indicates that we can combine the strengths of both approaches...\n\nLLMs + Tools: Combining language models with external tools (e.g., calculators, search engines, retrieval mechanisms, etc.) is a popular and effective approach for making these models more capable and effective. This approach is being explored via research advances like the Toolformer and even by OpenAI with the ChatGPT plugins store. Interestingly, integrating language models with useful tools is becoming quite simple. We can do it entirely via a prompting approach that provides descriptions of available tools and relies upon in-context learning capabilities to deduce the proper usage of each tool.\n\nDeep Learning as a Tool: For a while, research on language models only considered integration with relatively simple tools. What if we instead considered integrating language models with other, specialized deep learning models? The AI/ML community places a heavy emphasis on open-source software, meaning that many of the most powerful deep learning models are freely available online. Usually, these models come with well-written descriptions, called model cards, that can be used to provide all needed information about any model to an LLM. Then, these models can be easily integrated with an LLM via basic prompting techniques.\n\nHow can we do this? Deep learning models that are available on platforms like HuggingFace can be accessed via their associated model APIs. By teaching language models to call APIs associated with other, specialized deep learning models, we can construct a system that uses the language model as a controller (or brain) to coordinate the solution of a problem by planning and delegating subtasks to different APIs.\n\n“By providing only the model descriptions, HuggingGPT can continuously and conveniently integrate diverse expert models from AI communities, without altering any structure or prompt settings. This open and continuous manner brings us one step closer to realizing artificial general intelligence.” - from HuggingGPT\n\nSome Examples: Two recent publications have attempted to realize the goal of integrating language models with other deep learning models. HuggingGPT leverages paid APIs (e.g., for GPT-3.5 and GPT-4) and a prompting approach to teach language models to leverage specialized models available via HuggingFace. This approach works well, but it is highly dependent upon the capabilities of the underlying language model and only works for a fixed number of well-documented model APIs. Gorilla explores a more reliable and large-scale approach via open-source models (i.e., LLaMA-7B) and fine-tuning. More specifically, it curates a fine-tuning dataset of over 1,600 different model APIs, then fine-tunes an open-source language model (using the self-instruct framework) to learn how to leverage these APIs. The resulting Gorilla model is surprisingly capable of leveraging many different model APIs to solve complex problems. Plus, it can even adapt to real-time changes in model documentation by leveraging a retrieval-aware fine-tuning approach.\n\nTL;DR: There are a lot of “narrow expert” deep learning models out there that solve tasks extremely accurately. Modern large language models take an orthogonal approach of solving many different problems with a single model—they are foundation models! Both of these approaches are viable, and we can combine them by using language models as a controller that learns to call the APIs of specialized models when solving a problem.	t	t	code interpreter	t	f
