1669811217148289026	1768931599497023134	cwolferesearch	2023-06-16 20:56:32	Next-token prediction is the workhorse behind all modern advancements in large language models (LLMs) due to its use in training these models over unlabeled text. But, how exactly does this next-token prediction (or language modeling) objective work? Let’s take a deeper look…\n\nthe basics. The next-token prediction objective is used for training LLMs in a self-supervised manner. Put simply, this means that we repeatedly perform the following two steps:\n\n1. Sample some text from the dataset\n2. Train the model to predict the token that comes after each token within the sampled text\n\nThis objective is self-supervised because we have access to an entire corpus of text. Thus, the ground truth next token is always known! No explicit labeling (e.g., from human annotators) is required to obtain this.\n\ndecoder-only transformers. LLMs use decoder-only transformers as their underlying architecture. The representation formed by this model for each token within a sequence depends only upon the tokens that precede it. As such, we can independently (and in parallel) predict the next token for all tokens within a sequence by just:\n\n- Passing the sequence of tokens through all layers of the decoder-only transformer model\n- Considering the final output embedding for each token within the sequence\n- Treating next-token prediction as a classification problem over all tokens in our vocabulary that takes the current token's embedding as input\n\nWe can apply the next-token prediction loss over the entire sequence that has been passed through a decoder-only transformer and train the LLM using (stochastic) gradient descent!\n\nnext-token prediction in math. Consider a sequence of tokens given by U = [u1, u2, …]. Given a decoder-only transformer with parameters theta, the language modeling objective tries to maximize the conditional probability of a token given preceding tokens (see image for full expression). In other words, we maximize the probability of the model predicting the correct next token, given preceding tokens as context!\n\nperforming inference. We now understand the next-token prediction objective, but how does this teach an LLM to output coherent sequences of text? Well, generating text is just next-token prediction! We can just follow the steps below:\n\n- Consider a current sequence of tokens\n- Generate the next token using the LLM\n- Append this token to the sequence\n- Repeat\n\nThis autoregressive process is called “decoding” within the LLM community, and there are several different types of decoding we can perform (e.g., greedy decoding, nucleus sampling, etc.).\n\nTL;DR: The next-token prediction (or language modeling) objective is a self-supervised objective that is used heavily by LLMs for both pre-training and (supervised) fine-tuning. It operates by trying to continually classify the token that comes after the current token within a sequence of text, and we can apply it over an entire sequence of tokens at once (i.e., with a single forward pass) during training due to the use of a decoder-only transformer. Because it also mimics the decoding procedure used to generate text, next-token prediction is a fitting and efficient objective for training LLMs.	t	f	explainer	f	f
